        <div id="Desc"><h3>Description</h3>

            <p>
                Cancer is not just a one disease but a collection of many related diseases. Our body is made up of trillions of cells. Normally they grow and divide to form new cells as the body needs them. When cells grow and become damaged they die and new cells take their place. It is the ordinary process. But when cancer matures, that process breaks down and cells become more and more abnormal. Old or damaged cells do not die.  They form new cells when they are not needed and divide endlessly forming growths called ‘tumors’.  </p>

                <p>  
                Most cancers form solid tumors instead of blood cancers. These tumors are malicious and they can spread into nearby tissues and also sometimes they can travel to distant places in the body through the blood and form new tumors far from the original tumor. ‘Benign tumors’ do not spread like malicious tumors, when they are removed they do not grow again but unlike other tumors elsewhere in the body ‘brain benign tumors’ can be life threating.
                </p>

                <br>

                <img src="CTS-_-CTSR-g001.gif">

                <br>

                <p>It is not clearly identified why one person develops cancer and other person doesn’t. But researches show the factors which increase the risk of cancer. </p>

                <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Age</li>
                    <p>
                According to the most recent statistical data the median age of a cancer diagnosis is 66. It means that half of cancer victims are below this age and half of victims are above this. So the ‘age’ has become the most important risk factor for cancer overall. But keep in mind that the disease can occur at any age.
                            </p>

                    <li>Alcohol</li>
                    <p>
                Drinking alcohol can increase the risk of cancer of the mouth, throat, esophagus, larynx (voice box), liver, and breast. The more you drink, the higher your risk. The risk is much higher for those who drink alcohol and use tobacco. </p>
                <p>
                It has been suggested that certain substances in red wine has anticancer properties. But it is not said that drinking red wine reduces the risk of cancer.
                </p>

            <li>Cancer causing substances in the environment</li>
            <p>
                People can avoid some cancer-causing exposures, such as tobacco smoke and the sun’s rays. But there are some factors that are harder to avoid, especially when they are in the air we breathe, the water we drink, the food we eat, or the materials we use to do our jobs. Scientists are studying which exposures may cause or contribute to the development of cancer. So it is useful for the people as they could understand and avoid those factors. 
                </p>
                <p>
                Aflatoxins, Aristolochic Acids, Arsenic, Asbestos, Benzene, Cadmium, Wood Dust, and Mineral Oils are some of them.
                </p>

            <li> Radiation</li>
            <p>
                Certain wave length radiation that is called ‘ionizing radiation’, damages DNA and cause cancer. These radiations include radon, x-rays, gamma rays, and other forms of high-energy radiation.
                </p>
                <p>
                ‘Non ionizing radiation’ that are lower energized forms do not damage DNA. Such as visible light and the energy from cell phones and electromagnetic fields.
                </p>

                <li>Sunlight</li>
                <p>
                Earth has a shield called Ozone and it is the protector who protects us from ultraviolent radiations of sunrays. But as a result of bad human habits of polluting the environment the shield is damaged now and UV rays come down. So we must limit the amount of time we spend in the sun as these UV rays can cause to skin cancers. It is important to keep in mind that UV radiation is reflected by sand, water, snow, and ice and can go through windshields and windows.</p>

                <p>
                Protective clothing is the best way to lessen UV damage (wear long sleeves, long pants, a hat with a wide brim, and sunglasses with lenses that absorb UV radiation)
                </p>

